article.description:
Gwen Jackson scored 26 points to lead No. 4 Tennessee to a 92-79 win at No. 12 Arkansas on Thursday
night.
article.headline: Jackson scores 26 points for Tennessee
article.linkText: Lady Vols survive scare from Arkansas
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said she
was ready to take responsibility if her No. 4 Lady Volunteers
succumbed to  Arkansas (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP) on Thursday.

	   Fortunately, she didn't have to blame anyone, as the Lady
Volunteers downed the Lady Razorbacks, 92-79, to snap Arkansas'
10-game winning streak at home.

	   "I trusted our players at the end of the first half, and I told
them I wanted to trust them again Sunday in Nashville (against
Vanderbilt)," Summitt said. "But they have to take care of
business when they come off the bench and there's a big lead. There
just didn't seem to be a real sense of urgency at that point."

	   Gwen Jackson scored 26 points to lead Tennessee. Shyra Ely
scored 16 of the Tennessee bench's 26 points

	   Sarah Pfeifer was the only Arkansas player to score off the
bench.

	"We only had two points from our bench and that cannot
happen," Arkansas coach Gary Blair said. "A lot of times my bench
was getting beat on transition defense and that's why I couldn't
play them very long, so I had to play my kids that were a little
bit tired but at least they had been through that experience
before."

	   Arkansas (16-5, 3-3 SEC) trailed 47-31 at the half but fought
back to 75-72 late in the game. However, Tennessee (17-3, 6-0)
outscored the Lady Razorbacks 17-7 the rest of the way to pull away
for the win.

	  "I think that the key to being a great offensive player is to
make them work for everything they get," Tennessee's Kara Lawson
said. "Make them work for the ball, and when they do get the ball,
then make them take contested shots, and I thought we did a great
job of that."

	   Lawson added 17 points for the Lady Volunteers, and Ashley
Robinson contributed 11.

	   Shameka Christon scored 21 points for the Lady Razorbacks, India
Lewis added 16 points and Lakishia Harper and Dana Cherry each had
14.

	   Arkansas couldn't simulate Tennessee's athleticism and speed in
practice, Blair said, and that hurt the Lady Razorbacks in the long
run.

	  "We faced the best basketball team that we have faced this year
so far," Blair said. "If that team can go on the road and play
with the speed that they did in the first half, there's a lot of
good things in front of that basketball team."

	   An Arkansas' surge midway through the second half was sparked by
a pair of 3-pointers by Christon and another by Lewis. Cherry
weaved through traffic in the lane for a layup to bring Arkansas
within three at 64-61.

"We were taking the same shots and the defense was still right
on us, we were just hitting them in the second half," Lewis said.
"As a shooter you just keep shooting and hope they start falling,
and they did for us in the second half."

	   Tennessee switched from man-to-man to zone defense in the second
half to shut down Christon and Lewis, Summitt said, but both
players were scoring from the perimeter, even with hands in their
faces.

	   The 11,014 fans got into the game with a roar when Lewis hit a
three to get within three at 75-72, but three baskets by the Lady
Volunteers put them back up by nine with 3:55 left to play.

	"I think we were more focused on at least trying to contain
them if we could not stop them," Christon said. "They're a good
team and of course they're going to score. ... In the second half I
think we did a better job of trying to keep them from scoring."
